        {
          "id": 60062,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Cleidocranial dysostosis</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 60063,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Osteogenesis Imperfecta</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A mother brings her child with features of multiple teeth and a soft skull. On examination, the child is able to touch his both shoulder joints. On further evaluation, he is found to have defective membranous ossification. The images of his findings are given below. What is your diagnosis based on the features?</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/26/picture5_88c0u6E.jpg\" style=\"height:235px; width:300px\" /></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6528182",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32839,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. C. Cleidocranial dysostosis</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The clinical features is suggestive of Cleidocranial dysostosis. </span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The key features of this condition include:</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Clavicles </strong>may be <strong>underdeveloped or absent</strong>. Most <strong>common defect </strong>is the <strong>loss of lateral 1/3rd clavicle </strong>&gt; <strong>loss of middle third clavicle</strong>. Due to absence of clavicle shoulders look droopy, chest appears narrow &amp; when B/L loss occurs both shoulders can touch each other in front of the chest.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Delayed closure of fontanelles </strong>and <strong>cranial sutures</strong>, leading to a <strong>soft skull</strong>.</span></span></span><br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Supernumerary teeth </strong>and <strong>dental abnormalities</strong>.</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> High arched palate is also seen.</span></span></span><br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Defective ossification</strong>, particularly <strong>affecting membranous bones</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>A:</strong><strong> Chondro-osteodystrophy:</strong> This <strong>term is not commonly used in clinical practice </strong>and does not specifically match the features described in the scenario.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>B: Shoulder Dislocation:</strong> While the <strong>ability to touch the shoulder joints together </strong>might suggest <strong>joint laxity</strong>, the <strong>systemic features </strong>of <strong>multiple teeth </strong>and a <strong>soft skull </strong>are not consistent with a simple shoulder dislocation.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>D: Osteogenesis Imperfecta:</strong> This condition is <strong>primarily characterized by brittle bones </strong>that <strong>fracture easily</strong>, which is not described in the provided scenario.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Cleidocranial dysostosis/ cleidocranial dysplasia</strong>, is a <strong>rare genetic </strong>(autosomal dominant) associated with <strong>mutations in the RUNX2 gene</strong>, which plays a critical role in <strong>bone development and ossification</strong>. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">- Nelson 21<sup>st</sup> EDITION page 14389</span></strong></span></span></p>",
