          "id": 60075,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Salmonella enteritidis</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A mother brings her child with features of fever, swelling and pain during movement of leg. On physical examination, signs of inflammation were present. CBC examination reveals the increased levels of neutrophils along with a microcytic anaemia. A case of osteomyelitis is suspected. On taking history, the child is found to have sickle cell disease. Which of the following organisms is responsible for osteomyelitis in this case?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4197237",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32841,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. D) Salmonella enteritidis</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">In patients with <strong>sickle cell disease</strong>, the risk of <strong>osteomyelitis is increased </strong>due to <strong>infarction and subsequent infection </strong>of <strong>bone tissue</strong>. While <strong>Staphylococcus aureus </strong>is the most common <strong>cause of osteomyelitis </strong>in the <strong>general population</strong>, patients with <strong>sickle cell disease </strong>have an <strong>increased susceptibility to Salmonella enteritidis infections</strong>, making it a more likely cause in this context.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>A. Streptococcus pyogenes:</strong> While this <strong>organism can cause osteomyelitis</strong>, it is less commonly associated with osteomyelitis in patients with sickle cell disease compared to Salmonella species.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>B. Staphylococcus aureus:</strong> Although S. aureus is the most <strong>common cause of osteomyelitis </strong>overall, in the context of sickle cell disease, Salmonella species are more commonly implicated.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>C. Pseudomonas:</strong> This <strong>organism </strong>is more <strong>commonly associated with osteomyelitis in IV drug users</strong>, individuals with puncture wounds or those who are immunocompromised, but not specifically in sickle cell disease.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Organisms responsible for osteomyelitis are:</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">In <strong>normal population</strong>- <strong>Staphylococcus aureus</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">In <strong>sickle cell patients</strong>- <strong>Salmonella enteritidis</strong> is the M/C cause.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">- Nelson 21<sup>st</sup> Edition page 6044</span></strong></span></span></p>",
