          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Osteogenesis imperfecta and COL1A1</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 59811,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Marfan&rsquo;s syndrome and COL4A1</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">An 8-year-old girl named Rohini is brought to the clinic by her father due to a history of frequent falls. Initial X-rays reveal multiple fractures at various stages of healing, accompanied by numerous bruises on her skin. Given the suspicious nature of the injuries, child abuse is considered. However, upon a thorough examination, Rohini is found to have short stature, blue sclera, and deformities in her long bones and spine, leading to a re-evaluation of the initial suspicion towards a genetic disorder involving collagen. Based on Rohini&#39;s clinical presentation, what is the most likely diagnosis, and which gene is implicated in her condition?</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/26/picture2_6c3xOzj.jpg\" style=\"height:235px; width:300px\" /></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6965860",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32840,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. C. Osteogenesis imperfecta and COL1A1</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The diagnosis based on the Rohini&rsquo;s history is <strong>Osteogenesis imperfecta </strong>and it is <strong>Autosomal Dominant</strong> in nature. The <strong>Clinical features</strong> include:</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Multiple fractures:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> recurrent fractures, which can occur with minimal or no trauma causing deformities or shortening of limbs.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Blue sclera</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: It&rsquo;s due to the underlying connective tissue abnormalities.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Dental problems</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Brittle teeth that break easily or wear down quickly.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Hearing loss</span></strong> </span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Skeletal deformities</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: scoliosis (curvature of the spine), kyphosis (hunchback), or pectus excavatum (sunken chest).</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Short stature:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> due to the impact of skeletal abnormalities on bone growth.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Easy bruising</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Osteogenesis imperfecta can cause easy bruising or bleeding, particularly in people with severe forms of the condition.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A: Osteogenesis imperfecta and COL4A1: </span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">This option is <strong>incorrect </strong>because OI is typically <strong>associated with mutations </strong>in the <strong>COL1A1 or COL1A2 genes</strong>, not COL4A1.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">B: Marfan&rsquo;s syndrome and COL1A1</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Marfan syndrome is a <strong>disorder that affects connective tissue</strong>, characterized by <strong>tall stature, long limbs</strong>, and <strong>cardiovascular abnormalities</strong>, among others. It is most commonly caused by mutations in the FBN1 gene, not COL1A1, and does not typically result in fractures or blue sclera as seen in OI.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">D: Marfan&rsquo;s syndrome and COL4A1:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Marfan syndrome is <strong>not associated with mutations in the COL4A1 gene</strong>. COL4A1 mutations are linked to different conditions, such as certain types of cerebral small vessel disease.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Blue sclera</strong>, <strong>bone deformities</strong>, <strong>short stature</strong>, and a history of <strong>multiple fractures</strong>, are <strong>classic for Osteogenesis Imperfecta </strong>(OI), a <strong>genetic disorder </strong>caused by <strong>mutations in the COL1A1 </strong>or <strong>COL1A2 genes</strong>, which <strong>encode type I collagen</strong>, a crucial component of bone, skin, and other connective tissues.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">- Nelson 20<sup>th</sup> Edition, Page No-3423</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">.</span></span></p>",
